HEADWORD: Albion
<hw>Al"bi*on</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. from the
same root as Gael. <ets>alp</ets> a height or hill. ⟦ldquo⟧It may have
been bestowed on the land lying behind the white cliffs visible from the
coast of Gaul. <ets>Albany</ets>, the old name of Scotland, means
probably the ⟦ldquo⟧hilly land.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>I. Taylor.</au>]</ety>
<def>An ancient name of England, still retained in poetry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In that nook-shotten isle of <qex>Albion</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Albite</ent>⟦br⟧
